g tech companies like Google (GOOG) are in a massive spending spree. They'r=
e pouring huge amounts of money into building data centers, servers, and AI=
 infrastructure (called <strong>capex</strong>). This spending is so big th=
at it's swallowing up almost all their <strong>free cash flow</strong> =E2=
=80=94 the actual money left over after running the business. Whether Googl=
e can grow fast enough to justify the spending and the high valuation is th=
e real question.</p><h3>The Bear Case</h3><ul><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0=
">Google is trading at an all time crazy-high <strong>133x free cash flow</=
strong> multiple. Before COVID, it was only around 20x. That's a huge jump,=
 and the actual cash flow hasn't grown much since 2021.</p></li><li><p styl=
e=3D"margin:10px 0">In 2025, Google Cloud made $59 billion in revenue. But =
in 2026, they're planning to spend <strong>$175=E2=80=93185 billion</strong=
> on capex. That's spending <strong>3x</strong> their cloud revenue just to=
 build stuff.</p></li><li><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">AI Overviews (Google's=
 new AI answers that appear at the top of search) are cannabalizing their a=
d business because people get answers without clicking on ads.</p></li></ul=
><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Investment firm GQG are screaming: "This is uns=
ustainable! Google is spending way more than it makes, and the stock is way=
 too expensive."</p><h3>The Counter-Argument </h3><ul><li><p style=3D"margi=
n:10px 0">The drop in free cash flow isn't because Google is becoming less =
profitable. It's <strong>almost entirely</strong> because they're spending =
so much on growth right now. Their actual operating cash flow is still huge=
=2E</p></li><li><p style=3D"margin:10px=20=
0">Google is already putting ads insi=
de the AI Overviews, so they're not losing all that ad money.</p></li><li><=
p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Unlike 2022 (when Google stock crashed), Google n=
ow has a fast-growing cloud business that's becoming a real second engine.<=
/p></li></ul><h3>Bottom Line</h3><p style=3D"margin:10px 0">Both sides have=
 a point. Google is still an incredibly strong company. <strong>But</strong=
> spending this much money means there's very little room for error. The st=
ock price leaves almost no margin of safety if things don't go perfectly. E=
xpect the FUD to also hit META, AMZN, MSFT and even TSLA (although they are=
 spending a lot less). </p><p style=3D"margin:10px 0"></p><p></p></div></td=
></tr>
